# Frontend Standards

## Provider Composition Order

The provider stack is fixed and intentional — do not reorder:

```
QueryClientProvider          ← outermost: data fetching infra
  → AuthProvider             ← auth state (Cognito/Amplify)
    → ClientConfigProvider   ← fetches client-config.json at startup
      → ThemeProvider        ← consumes config, applies CSS vars
        → App               ← routes and pages
```

Each provider has a single responsibility. ClientConfigProvider is the single owner of runtime client config. ThemeProvider reads theme tokens from it — never fetches independently.

## Config-Driven Navigation

Sidebar navigation items are derived from feature flags via ClientConfigProvider. Never hardcode route lists or `clientKey === 'x'` conditionals.

- `client-config.json` declares `navigation[]` with `featureKey` references
- PortalLayout filters items by `features[featureKey]`
- Adding a new page: add a nav entry in config + a route in App.tsx + the page component

## Auth Visibility vs Authorization

Frontend feature flags (`features.*` in client-config.json) are UX visibility controls only — they hide UI elements. Backend capability bundle enforcement is the authorization layer. Never rely on hidden routes for security.

## Shell-First Composition

PortalLayout is the single layout wrapper (sidebar + header + content). Do not create per-page sidebar or header assembly. All portal pages render inside PortalLayout as children.

## No Hand-Written Duplicate API Types

All API request/response types come from `packages/contracts/` via the generation pipeline (`npm run generate-types`). Never hand-write types that duplicate contract models. Import from `@/types/generated/` for contract types.

## Components

- Functional components only, hooks-first. No class components.
- One component per file.
- Co-locate tests with components or in `__tests__/`.
- Prefix shared components with project namespace if extracting to a library.

## Styling

- Tailwind utility classes only. No CSS modules, no styled-components, no inline `style` props.
- Use `cn()` (clsx + tailwind-merge) for conditional classes.
- Theme values accessed via CSS custom properties: `text-primary`, `bg-accent`, `font-sans`.

## State Management

- Server state: TanStack React Query (`@tanstack/react-query`).
- Client state: React Context for cross-cutting concerns, local `useState` otherwise.
- Avoid prop drilling beyond 2 levels — use context or composition.

## Performance

- Only runtime config loading (`ClientConfigProvider`) may block initial shell render; all other provider work should be non-blocking.
- Lazy-load page components with `React.lazy()` + `Suspense`.
- Memoize expensive computations with `useMemo`.
- Use virtualization for long lists.

## Testing

- Every new component gets a co-located or integration test.
- Vitest + React Testing Library (RTL).
- Test behavior, not implementation details.
- Mock providers using test wrappers (see `__tests__/setup.ts`).

## Accessibility

- Semantic HTML: use `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<aside>`, `<header>`, `<button>` — not generic `<div>` for interactive elements.
- `aria-label` on interactive elements without visible text labels.
- Keyboard navigation: all interactive elements must be focusable and operable via keyboard.
- Color contrast: follow WCAG 2.1 AA minimums.

## Security

- Sanitize user input before rendering.
- Never store tokens in localStorage — use Amplify session management.
- Validate environment variables at build time via `env.ts`.
